    Hey I had the same issue and I was able to solve it, I would leave the steps I follow to fix

    Step 1. Install Creative Cloud 5.7.0.1307 or install it from here (mega.nz/file/yaZBhDoB#p3nTh7-Bdg3Li1SUaAjcYd33Zh6GCkLJ87LJLtDaW9Y) This link is mine I uploaded the one I installed so do not worry .

    Step 3. After the installation is done go to /Library/Application Support/Adobe and locate the folder name "Caps" and delete it or send it to Trash. "You can easily go to the location by Holding Shift+Command+G on your desktop."

    Step 4. just try to install the Adobe Application you were trying to install before and it should work 100% with no issue.

    However, there is an additional step to be done which is in the instructions you know, those README files nobody reads which is that you should start the application before applying the no-account patch, so that it properly initialises all directories on disk (thus dealing with the 'missing' caps directory that so many complain about). This first-time run will take a long time that's normal. Once it finishes doing its job and allows you to start your 7-day trial, you quit the application. Then you apply the no-account patch. And afterwards, you're good to go! (The app, because it "knows" it should not connect to the Internet, will actually be quite faster than usually an added bonus)

    GwynethLlewelyn commented on Dec 7, 2024

    Gwyneth Llewelyn
    on Dec 7, 2024
    More actions

    @AvianHorde sorry for replying only today, a month after your question!

    Formerly (i.e., before Adobe Creative Cloud existed), patches focused on overriding installed licence files, or generating 'valid' licences from a key generator (or sometimes both).

    With Adobe Creative Cloud, disk-based licence files are mostly obsolete, as all authentication is done on the Internet, so different strategies have to be used instead. The first and perhaps the more common method is to patch the apps to prevent them to contact the Adobe servers on the Internet; since Internet access is not necessarily always available (think of a legitimate Adobe Photoshop user, doing their artistic creations on a long intercontinental plane trip), Adobe's apps have 'fallback' methods to cope with that: most tools will work even without Internet access. One popular early method, which did not require any patching to be done, was simply to locally block access to all Adobe servers, by simply pointing them to 127.0.0.1 (localhost) instead in /etc/hosts. This would make the Adobe apps time out on the connections (since they resolved the address to a valid IP address, albeit one where 'nothing' was listening), forcing them to enter the 'Internetless' mode instead. An alternative was to add a long list of well-known IP addresses used by Adobe to the firewall. The effect was pretty much the same.

    Adobe quickly caught up with that, and not only added (and replaced) a lot of the IP addresses, as well as checking if the server names were accessible or blocked by either trick. What the patches did was to remove that extra bit of code and making the Adobe apps fall back to the old method(s) instead. Eventually, some patches were released which would change the apps so that these never contacted the Internet in any circumstance whatsoever; this, in turn, meant that all the complexities of manually changing /etc/hosts and/or configuring the firewall rules became unnecessary: the patch would work before the actual calls were made.

    Adobe, to circumvent those patches, just distributed the Internet-calling code all over the place, making it much more difficult to develop (and maintain) a 'universal patch' that would work across versions.

    The second approach, what I call the 'no-account patch', is slightly more clever. You see, all Adobe apps have a trial mode, where you can have access to all functionality before signing in, to give you the ability to 'test before you buy'. This is tied to the timer that will allow you to use everything until a certain number of days has elapsed, and then either blocks all functionality or allows you to sign in with a registered (and paying) account, which will unblock the functionality again.

    This was exploited by the 'no-account patch'. One nave (but originally very effective!) way of doing so was simply to disable the timer. Adobe quickly dealt with that, possibly by having the timer both locally and remotely (i.e., also running on their own servers); if they didn't match, Adobe would (correctly) assume that the app was breached and block all functionality to it. This is rather effective, since it also meant that reinstalling everything (or even starting the Mac with a wrong, fake date which would wreak havoc with everything else running on the system anyway) would have no effect: Adobe would now have a digital signature of the Mac with an expired timer on their servers, and, because of that, every time you logged in even from a pristinely clean installation Adobe would immediately know that, whatever the app said, that account on that Mac was trying to access it beyond the trial phase, and should therefore be prevented to launch.

    Contemporary 'no-account' patches, in an attempt to work around these issues, work slightly differently. Instead of the brute-force approach of disabling/resetting the timer, it somehow manages to force the app to enter the pre-trial mode i.e., immediately before the timer even starts! As such, the user's status becomes undefined: did it go through the trial phase successfully or not? More specifically, if that user already went through the whole trial phase but is still being flagged as 'in trial', what is supposed to happen?

    Allegedly, this is what the 'no-account patch' manages to do: it subverts the whole system, somehow managing to convince the Adobe servers that it is perfectly legitimate to have no account logged in and still have permanent access to all web-based functionality.

    Well, not all, of course anything AI-related, for instance, does require logging in, and so does the access to the cloud-stored documents but most of the remaining tools will continue to work and not complain much.

    The only issue with the 'no-account patch' is that, since the remaining Adobe subsystem can remain in place, it will constantly try to persuade you to do an upgrade to the latest version. If that version is not supported by the patch itself, then you'll have to start from scratch download the latest version that is still patchable, clean up your system from everything Adobe-related, and reinstall, and apply the patch again... next time, do not agree to upgrade!

    How do you know which patch does what? Well, since that depends so much on who actually designed, packaged, distributed, and maintained the patch, there is no rule, really. Some patch developers will tell in advance what exactly their patch does. Some skip all the technical details altogether and just let the patch be magically applied. From y recent experience in the past year or two, the 'no-account patches' seem to be more popular at the moment, but who knows what will come in the future?...

    ReactKodamaAkira

    UPDATE Feb 2024:

    I managed to install Lightroom Classic 11 on a brand new Mac (intel)

    1. Install CC5 (link somewhere above)
    2. As soon as CC opens, disconnect from the internet (it WILL update even if you turn Auto Updates off)
    3. In CC, turn off Auto Update
    4. In CC, turn off Auto start (or something along these lines)
    5. Quit CC completely
    6. OPTIONAL: restart your Mac
    7. re-connect to the internet
    8. Use adobe-packager to download LTRM v11.0
    9. Install
    10. Open Lightroom once
    11. Close Lightroom
    12. Crack with Adobe Activation tool from MacKed

    Version 11.0 was the newest one I managed to install. Everything above that will give you an JSON or other error.

    Step 3. After the installation is done go to /Library/Application Support/Adobe and locate the folder name "Caps" and delete it or send it to Trash. "You can easily go to the location by Holding Shift+Command+G on your desktop."

    Step 4. just try to install the Adobe Application you were trying to install before and it should work 100% with no issue.

    I just did this and worked 100% for me. if you have any questions, add me on Discord FW #0880

    [SOLUTION #2]

    Suppose you don't want to download this Creative Cloud link and are just doing it the kosher way (from whatever website you got it from). In that case, the reason it's instant updating is simply because your Wi-Fi is too fast, and also, Adobe is trying to spam that update because it hates you.

    Basically, the problem is: when Creative Cloud opens, the update is already in the queue (before you've even gotten to preferences), so when you go to disable it, it won't get rid of the update that's already in the queue, making it update to 7.21..... before you can do anything about it.

    Solution: Uninstall Creative Cloud. And when you redownload it, do the steps from 3-4 (in the replied comment). It basically gets rid of(?) the cloud sync system

    (It will redownload these files later, so no problem there, but the point is to stop it from updating before you can disable it.)
